5. Smart Contract Overview

The smart contract is named MedTwinTrust.

Its responsibility is to securely store document fingerprints (hashes) and maintain an immutable record of medical documents.

The contract stores:

Document Hash
Doctor Wallet Address
Timestamp

The contract does not store:

PDF files
Medical reports
Patient information
Images

This design keeps medical information private while ensuring authenticity can be verified later.

6. Smart Contract Functions
recordSignature(bytes32 docHash)

Purpose:

Stores a new medical document hash.

Functionality:

Accepts a keccak256 hash.
Saves the doctor's wallet address.
Stores the current blockchain timestamp.
Rejects duplicate hashes.
verify(bytes32 docHash)

Purpose:

Checks whether a document hash already exists.

Returns:

Doctor Wallet Address
Timestamp
Exists (true/false)
isRecorded(bytes32 docHash)

Purpose:

Returns only whether a document has already been registered.

Return Type:

bool
7. Blockchain Workflow

The blockchain does not receive PDF files directly.

Instead, it receives a cryptographic hash generated from the uploaded document.

Workflow:

User Uploads PDF
        │
        ▼
React Frontend
        │
        ▼
FastAPI Backend
        │
Reads PDF
        │
Generates keccak256 Hash
        │
        ▼
recordSignature(hash)
        │
        ▼
Polygon Blockchain

Only the generated hash is stored on-chain.

8. Why the PDF Is Not Stored on Blockchain

Storing complete medical reports directly on-chain is not recommended because:

Large files are expensive to store.
Every node would permanently store the document.
Medical data should remain private.

Instead:

PDF

↓

keccak256()

↓

32-byte Hash

↓

Stored on Blockchain

This approach ensures:

Privacy
Lower transaction cost
Fast verification
Immutable proof of existence
9. Verification Process

When a document needs verification:

Upload the PDF again.
Generate the keccak256 hash.
Call:
verify(hash)

If the returned value is:

exists = true

The document is authentic.

If:

exists = false

The uploaded document has never been recorded or has been modified.

10. Unit Testing

The contract was tested using Hardhat.

Test cases include:

Test 1

Successful document registration.

Expected Result:

Pass

Test 2

Duplicate document registration.

Expected Result:

Transaction reverts.

Test 3

Verify unknown hash.

Expected Result:

exists = false
Test 4

Verify existing document.

Expected Result:

Doctor address matches
Timestamp exists
exists = true
11. Deployment

The smart contract was deployed on:

Polygon Amoy Testnet

Deployment performed using:

npx hardhat run scripts/deploy.js --network amoy

Deployment completed successfully.

12. ABI Generation

After compilation:

npx hardhat compile

Hardhat generated:

artifacts/contracts/
    MedTwinTrust.sol/
        MedTwinTrust.json

The ABI was copied into:

blockchain/abi/

The backend team can use this ABI for integration with Ethers.js.

13. Backend Integration

The blockchain module expects:

bytes32 docHash

Backend responsibilities:

Receive uploaded PDF.
Read file.
Generate:
keccak256(pdfBytes)
Call:
recordSignature(hash)

The blockchain stores only the hash.

14. Example Integration

Store document:

recordSignature(hash)

Verify document:

verify(hash)

No blockchain changes are required in the frontend.

15. Security Features

Implemented security measures include:

Duplicate prevention
Immutable blockchain storage
Timestamp recording
Doctor wallet recording
Hash-based verification
Privacy-preserving design
16. Advantages
Immutable records
Tamper detection
Low blockchain storage cost
No patient information stored on-chain
Easy backend integration
Transparent audit trail
17. Limitations

The blockchain module does not:

Store PDF files.
Read uploaded documents.
Generate hashes from files.

Hash generation is expected to be handled by the backend before interacting with the smart contract.

